{"id":"2202.08734","submitter":"Tommaso Rigon","authors":"Tommaso Rigon and Emanuele Aliverti","title":"Conjugate priors and bias reduction for logistic regression models","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"stat.ME","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Logistic regression models for binomial responses are routinely used in\nstatistical practice. However, the maximum likelihood estimate may not exist\ndue to data separability. We address this issue by considering a conjugate\nprior penalty which always produces finite estimates. Such a specification has\na clear Bayesian interpretation and enjoys several invariance properties,\nmaking it an appealing prior choice. We show that the proposed method leads to\nan accurate approximation of the reduced-bias approach of Firth (1993),\nresulting in estimators with smaller asymptotic bias than the\nmaximum-likelihood and whose existence is always guaranteed. Moreover, the\nconsidered penalized likelihood can be expressed as a genuine likelihood, in\nwhich the original data are replaced with a collection of pseudo-counts. Hence,\nour approach may leverage well established and scalable algorithms for logistic\nregression. We compare our estimator with alternative reduced-bias methods,\nvastly improving their computational performance and achieving appealing\ninferential results.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 17 Feb 2022 16:15:57 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-18"}
